description:
### Problem to solve

Add a sum of `Groups` to the `Users` view in the `Admin Area`.

This is expected to be much more complex than adding the sum of `Projects` https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/249590 for the reasons outlined below in `Additional notes`.

Parent epic: https://gitlab.com/groups/gitlab-org/-/epics/4432

### Proposal

Show the truncated total number of authorized `Groups` for each user.

![Users_list_with_group_and_project_count](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/uploads/b331c94862ff5250976551129658a686/Users_list_with_group_and_project_count.png)

### Implementation outline

1. Create a endpoint to get the truncated authorized `groups` count given an array of user IDs. Implemented in GraphQL (details below) - `2` ~backend

### GraphQL API

`groupCount` for a set of users can be obtained by accessing the [`users`](https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/api/graphql/#available-queries) GraphQL endpoint.

**Example request:**

```json
query {
  users(usernames: ["asubramanian1", "mwoolf"]){
    nodes{
      id
      avatarUrl
      name
      groupCount
    }
  }
}
```

**Example request:**

```json
{
  "data": {
    "users": {
      "nodes": [
        {
          "id": "gid://gitlab/User/1678249",
          "avatarUrl": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/4c8af02fcb6678db41bd8d3a29f9c1d8?s=80&d=identicon",
          "name": "Max Woolf",
          "groupCount": null
        },
        {
          "id": "gid://gitlab/User/1675776",
          "avatarUrl": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f2253d38808acfe769a32da952dbe91d?s=80&d=identicon",
          "name": "Aishwarya Subramanian",
          "groupCount": 18
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

### Access

- Administrator users can access the group count of all users in the system.
- Non-administrator users can access the group count of only self

### Feature Flag

The feature is gated behind the flag: `user_group_counts`, and is disabled by default.

### Additional notes

The additional complexity for **group** count is due to the performance concerns we've dicussed here and discovered in https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/39581#note_399390950, and the implementation is based on ~database and ~frontend maintainer feedback with the intent to get the page time below `100ms` by asynchronously loading the `groups` count.

Follow up from https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/41617#note_410928565

@dosuken123 wrote:

> This seems resulting in a security vulnerability that users could accidentally set a secret into the key `AUTO_DEVOPS_PLATFORM_TARGET` and the value will remain in plaintext forever. In fact, we already see that some users are setting a value neither `ECS` nor `FARGATE` in production database. Can you add a filter logic here not to allow invalid `target`?
